[Student "S"]
{Wow! Partner opens with a 2-bid and you have all of this?

Don't get carried away, it was a <b>WEAK</b> 2-bid. So even though you have 19 points partner has only 6-11. But even though it is possible that the total only comes to 25 you bid the game anyway, figuring that it will probably be at least 26.

South would play 4\H.

Click 

North plays 4\H. East leads the \SQ. 

<b>North plays 4\H. East leads the \SQ.</b>

Losers: \S 0 : \H 0 : \D 1 : \C 3 : Total = 4

There are two ways to get rid of one of those \C losers. You can lead up to the \CK, hoping that East holds \CA, or you can ruff it in dummy.

Suppose you try to combine both chances. Win the \SK, then play a small \H to your hand. Lead a \C and play dummy's \CK. West takes the \CA and plays another trump which you win in your hand. You play another \C but West wins this one also and leads another trump, removing dummy's last hope of ruffing a \C. Down 1.

Instead you could give up on the idea of leading toward the \CK and just lead a \C from dummy at trick 2. The defenders can win and lead a trump, but you play a second \C. They win this also but even if they lead a trump you can still ruff your third \C in dummy and make the game.

You can see that playing a \C from dummy will guarantee the contract.

You can also see that leading a \H back to your hand at trick 2 is a bad idea.

But did you see there is another way to reach your hand? You could play \SA then ruff a \S. This runs the small risk that West started with a singleton \S.}
[Play "W"]SQ

